description.value: Irregularly shaped sherd from a large pale-pink vessel,  the exterior covered with a light-green/cream slip. The sherd has been perforated after production with five round  drill-holes and the beginning of a further one. The same kind of drill-holes appear on a complete Klazomenian amphora, same provenance (EA 22343), in pairs, either side of cracks in the body, suggesting they were intended for fixing or consolidating the fragile or broken parts with ropes or staples.    Minimum diameter (40-45 cm), thickness (up to 1.6 cm), and slightly concave outside profile suggest that the container was an amphora, maybe of the "basket-handle" type. The repair also points out a secondary re-use, probably for containment of dry product like grain.
